ught, =E2=80=9CWhy is there no book about this man?=E2=80=9D

As it turns out, Olivier Meslay,
who became the director of the Clark in 2016, the year before Bell arrived,=
 had acquired a painting by Lethi=C3=A8re in his previous role as curator a=
t the Dallas Museum of Fine Art. The foundation was in place to begin assem=
bling a collection. At Christie=E2=80=99s in 2018, the Clark bid on ( https=
://www.christies.com/en/lot/lot-6136797?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%288%2F4%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F21%2F24=
%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617d=
a42abd12a ) a small version of Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s monumental painting,=
 Brutus condemning his sons, which had caused such a stir in London during =
his lifetime. The museum won the work for $852,500.

The Christie=E2=80=99s lot actually contained three different works of art:=
 the painting, an engraving of the image, and a sketch for the work. Not lo=
ng after, the Clark acquired a portfolio of a hundred drawings by Lethi=C3=
=A8re that had been part of the artist=E2=80=99s estate. Suddenly, with so =
many
works by Lethi=C3=A8re, the Clark was a leading institutional authority on =
the artist. Meslay and Bell decided to mount, as Bell put it, =E2=80=9Ca mo=
nographic exhibition about this talented and institutionally important pers=
on.=E2=80=9D It would become the first presentation of his work since the 1=
9th century.

$(ad3_title) ( https://pages.e.northerntrust.com/wm-valuing-appraising-tran=
sferring-art.html?utm_medium=3Dnative&utm_source=3Dpuck&utm_campaign=3Dwmna=
tional_grp-us-leadgen-insights-20240730&utm_content=3Dwall_power_newsletter=
&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F4%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWal=
l+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F21%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sourc=
e=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Twenty Years After

When the Lethi=C3=A8re show leaves the Clark, it will travel to the Louvre,=
 where the painter=E2=80=99s monumental works Brutus condemning his sons an=
d The Death of Virginia are housed. At 15 by 25 feet, the paintings are too=
 large to move. Even if they could be transported to Massachusetts (imagine=
 the cost!), the Clark doesn=E2=80=99t have enough space to show them along=
 with the rest of the exhibition.

At the Louvre, the show should be a triumphal homecoming for the boy from G=
uadeloupe, who survived and thrived throughout one of French history=E2=80=
=99s most tumultuous eras. But Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s story contains multi=
tudes, which Bell and her colleagues make great efforts to highlight.

Much of the exhibition just chronicles Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s artistic ach=
ievements. But his role in French society is a major theme, too. To illustr=
ate his
importance, the show prominently features Louis-L=C3=A9opold Boilly=E2=80=
=99s painting Meeting of Artists in Isabey=E2=80=99s Studio, which also bec=
ame a popular print. Lethi=C3=A8re dominates the image as its central and l=
argest figure, draped in a red cloak. =E2=80=9CIt portrays the avant-garde =
cultural figures of France,=E2=80=9D Bell told me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s al=
l of the new stars, none of the old guard of French cultural life. It was t=
he People magazine of the day.=E2=80=9D

Of course, Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s parentage also plays a large role in his=
 story. Around the time Boilly=E2=80=99s painting was made, Lethi=C3=A8re=
=E2=80=99s father was able to recognize him and his sister as his heirs. Ye=
ars later, Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s legitimacy would be questioned in a cour=
t case=E2=80=94the documents of which provide most of the historical materi=
al for what we know of his lineage=E2=80=94but Lethi=C3=A8re prevailed. The=
 issue was less that his mother had been a slave and more whether his fathe=
r had been legally married to another woman
at the time.

Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s Creole background was a central theme of his life. =
The show devotes a whole room to depictions of a wide cast of Afro-Caribbea=
n characters who were prominent in revolutionary, Napoleonic, and restorati=
on France=E2=80=94including Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s lifelong friend Alexand=
re Dumas=E2=80=99s father, a charismatic general born in Haiti to a French =
nobleman and a slave.

The Haitian revolution of the 1790s and Napoleon=E2=80=99s re-establishment=
 of slavery in the French colonies also provides a poignant backdrop to Let=
hi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s own story. Despite his success in France and his close=
 association with Napoleon=E2=80=99s brother, Lethi=C3=A8re maintained his =
revolutionary and republican sympathies, especially toward Haiti. He painte=
d an ode to the Haitian revolution, Oath of the Ancestors, and had his son =
make a dangerous secret journey to the island republic to deliver it. The H=
aitian government had agreed to lend the painting to the show before it was
overwhelmed by the current political crisis, which prevented the work from =
traveling.

End Notes=E2=80=A6

What a story! You don=E2=80=99t have to be a fan of Creole painters who bec=
ome courtiers to enjoy a trip to the Clark, especially in the summertime, w=
hen the Berkshires really do shine.

Mrs. Wall Power and I stayed at Tourists Welcome ( https://www.touristswelc=
ome.com/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F4%2F24%29&utm_conte=
nt=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F21%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&u=
tm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), a hipster motel de=
veloped by the bassist for Wilco, John Stirratt, and some partners. A few d=
ays before we checked in, judging by Instagram, there was a dry run of the =
Arrival Art fair at Tourists. The real fair will open in June of 2025. (Nea=
r as I can tell, the fair is a project by a group of Williams art alums. Th=
ere=E2=80=99s a whole story to be written about the Williams Mafia, but I=
=E2=80=99m not going to get
into it here. Maybe next summer.)

Until Tuesday, let me leave you with Andrew Russeth=E2=80=99s review ( http=
s://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/01/arts/design/stitch-by-stitch-pacita-abad-cro=
ssed-continents-and-cultures.html?searchResultPosition=3D1&utm_campaign=3DW=
all+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F4%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%287%2F21%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) of the Pacita Abad retrospective at MoMA PS1=
, which closes in September. You=E2=80=99re likely to hear a lot more about=
 Abad in the coming years: She=E2=80=99s got the potential to become a figu=
re like Basquiat that everyone will feel they missed out on. So don=E2=80=
=99t miss this chance to see her work in Queens.

Marion

