          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>I=E2=80=99ll tel=
l you more about Lethi=C3=A8re below. But first, a few notes from around th=
e art world=E2=80=A6</i><br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-=
size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:squ=
are;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>Coeur d=E2=80=99Alene Auction results=
</i>: The annual Coeur d=E2=80=99Alene auction of Western art made $17.2 mi=
llion last weekend with prices in the mid six figures for artists <b>Philip=
 R. Goodwin</b>, <b>William R. Leigh</b>, <b>Charles M. Russell</b>, <b>How=
ard Terpning</b>, and <b>Frederic Remington</b>.</li><br/><li><i>Bonhams ge=
ts new leadership</i>: Bonhams announced last week that <b>Chabi Nouri</b>,=
 the former chief executive of watchmaker Piaget, will become the auction h=
ouse=E2=80=99s new C.E.O. in October. Nouri will take over from <b>Bruno Vi=
nciguerra</b>, who left suddenly in February despite
having posted the company=E2=80=99s highest-ever annual gross revenues:  $1=
=2E14 billion in 2023. <br/><br/>Bonham=
s, now owned by the private equity fir=
m Epiris, has been pursuing an awkward strategy of trying to compete with i=
ts historic rivals (in the sense that they were all founded in 18th century=
 England), Christie=E2=80=99s, Sotheby=E2=80=99s, and Phillips. Part of Vin=
ciguerra=E2=80=99s mandate had been to bring client relationships from his =
former position as C.O.O. at Sotheby=E2=80=99s. Then Epiris acquired severa=
l European and American auction houses to expand Bonhams=E2=80=99s reach an=
d revenue. In 2023, a third of Bonhams=E2=80=99s sales took place in Europe=
, 30 percent were in North America, 19 percent were in the U.K., and 18 per=
cent were in Asia.<br/><br/>Epiris bought Bonhams six years ago and had bee=
n hoping to sell it in the run-up that produced 2023=E2=80=99s strong resul=
ts. Failing to produce an exit with the somewhat hasty strategy of bulking =
up through acquisitions, Epiris felt it needed to switch gears
and find a new C.E.O.<br/><br/>The problem with the strategy under Vincigue=
rra is that competing against the biggest auction houses requires a differe=
nt approach than rolling up smaller houses that sell lower-value lots. What=
 Bonhams <i>really</i> needs is to improve its infrastructure so it can pro=
cess and sell its high volume of lots across several still-independently op=
erated auction houses at higher margins. It=E2=80=99s not clear whether Nou=
ri has that skill set.<br/><br/>Hiring Nouri, a former partner at private e=
quity shop Mirabaud who spent a decade at Cartier before going to Piaget, i=
s in line with the trend toward convergence in the worlds of art, fashion, =
and luxury. But while the latter businesses are focused on production, desi=
gn, and marketing, auction houses are fundamentally <i>agency businesses</i=
>=E2=80=94an insight that was bequeathed to me by <b>Guillaume Cerutti</b>,=
 the C.E.O. of Christie=E2=80=99s, who once patiently explained why Christi=
e=E2=80=99s, although it has the same
shareholder as Kering, is managed as a separate business. (This insight may=
 explain why owner <b>Fran=C3=A7ois-Henri Pinault</b>, who acquired a major=
ity stake in CAA last year, has kept it separate from Kering, too.) We=E2=
=80=99ll see what Nouri has to say when she starts in October. </li><br/><l=
i><i>Australia gets a discount Gauguin</i>: The Australian National Gallery=
 has acquired <b>Paul Gauguin</b>=E2=80=99s The Blue Roof or Farm at Le Pou=
ldu, painted in Brittany in 1890, for $6.5 million from a private collector=
 through <b>Pilar Ordovas</b>=E2=80=99s gallery. The painting will be the f=
irst Gauguin to enter a public collection in Australia. It had been previou=
sly shown in London at Ordovas=E2=80=99s gallery before the owner, a privat=
e collector, loaned the work to the international exhibition <i>Gauguin=E2=
=80=99s World: Tona Iho, Tona Ao</i>, currently at the National Gallery of =
Australia. <br/><br/>The museum actually got <i>The Blue Roof</i> at a disc=
ount, considering its previous auction price of
$5.2 million in May 2000=E2=80=94equivalent to $9.5 million today. That=E2=
=80=99s a 32 percent drop in monetary value over the course of 24 years, ev=
en though several of Gauguin=E2=80=99s greatest Tahitian images have risen =
dramatically in price over the same period. In 2015, Tahitian painting <i>N=
afea Faa Ipoipo (When Will You Marry?)</i> was sold privately for $210 mill=
ion. Alas, the market for historical artists doesn=E2=80=99t rise in value =
in uniform ways: As some artists see intense price appreciation for works t=
hat are perceived to be A+ examples, other paintings lose value over time. =
</li><br/><li><i>At 25, Mass MoCA looks for a reboot</i>: <i>The Boston Glo=
be</i> <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1=
lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSSDUtS0ZaU0ZJdGhyM05ua2Q0dz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
