          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">When the Lethi=C3=
=A8re show leaves the Clark, it will travel to the Louvre, where the painte=
r=E2=80=99s monumental works <i>Brutus condemning his sons</i> and <i>The D=
eath of</i> <i>Virginia </i>are housed. At 15 by 25 feet, the paintings are=
 too large to move. Even if they could be transported to Massachusetts (ima=
gine the cost!), the Clark doesn=E2=80=99t have enough space to show them a=
long with the rest of the exhibition. <br/><br/>At the Louvre, the show sho=
uld be a triumphal homecoming for the boy from Guadeloupe, who survived and=
 thrived throughout one of French history=E2=80=99s most tumultuous eras. B=
ut Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s story contains multitudes, which Bell and her co=
lleagues make great efforts to highlight. <br/><br/>Much of the exhibition =
just chronicles Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s artistic achievements. But his role=
 in French society is a major theme, too. To illustrate his
importance, the show prominently features <b>Louis-L=C3=A9opold Boilly</b>=
=E2=80=99s painting <i>Meeting of Artists in Isabey=E2=80=99s Studio, </i>w=
hich also became a popular print<i>.</i> Lethi=C3=A8re dominates the image =
as its central and largest figure, draped in a red cloak. =E2=80=9CIt portr=
ays the avant-garde cultural figures of France,=E2=80=9D Bell told me. =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s all of the new stars, none of the old guard of French cu=
ltural life. It was the <i>People</i> magazine of the day.=E2=80=9D<br/><br=
/>Of course, Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s parentage also plays a large role in h=
is story. Around the time Boilly=E2=80=99s painting was made, Lethi=C3=A8re=
=E2=80=99s father was able to recognize him and his sister as his heirs. Ye=
ars later, Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s legitimacy would be questioned in a cour=
t case=E2=80=94the documents of which provide most of the historical materi=
al for what we know of his lineage=E2=80=94but Lethi=C3=A8re prevailed. The=
 issue was less that his mother had been a slave and more whether his fathe=
r had been legally married to another woman
at the time. <br/><br/>Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s Creole background was a cent=
ral theme of his life. The show devotes a whole room to depictions of a wid=
e cast of Afro-Caribbean characters who were prominent in revolutionary, Na=
poleonic, and restoration France=E2=80=94including Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s =
lifelong friend Alexandre Dumas=E2=80=99s father, a charismatic general bor=
n in Haiti to a French nobleman and a slave. <br/><br/>The Haitian revoluti=
on of the 1790s and Napoleon=E2=80=99s re-establishment of slavery in the F=
rench colonies also provides a poignant backdrop to Lethi=C3=A8re=E2=80=99s=
 own story. Despite his success in France and his close association with Na=
poleon=E2=80=99s brother, Lethi=C3=A8re maintained his revolutionary and re=
publican sympathies, especially toward Haiti. He painted an ode to the Hait=
ian revolution, <i>Oath of the Ancestors, </i>and had his son make a danger=
ous secret journey to the island republic to deliver it. The Haitian govern=
ment had agreed to lend the painting to the show before it was
overwhelmed by the current political crisis, which prevented the work from =
traveling. <br/></td>
         </tr>
